In fulfilment of the promise made in 2021, the Government of Japan has donated judo equipment to the  Lagos State Judo Association (LSJA). Speaking during the presentation of the first set of equipment to the LSJA, the Japanese ambassador to Nigeria, Matsunaga Kazuyoshi said they are ready to improve the profile of judo in Nigeria, adding  Lagos would continue to benefit from the gesture of Japanese government since the donation would not be a one-off event. He specifically hailed the efforts of the Chairman of LSJA Sheriff Hammed whose vision and passion for the sport has brought vibrancy to judo in the state.   Organisers set for MASA Isonyin Marathon     UCL: Man City, Liverpool book semi-final spots     EUROPA LEAGUE: Rangers’ Bassey available to face Braga   “I am so happy to be here today because what we are doing here today is to fulfil the promise I made on September 2021 where I promised to support the state with some equipment,” he said. “Fortunately when I went back to Japan, I was able to talk to an NGO in Japan who are eager to give judo equipment. “ This is just the first set of equipment and we believe this will be a continuous partnership that will help to teach the athletes the virtues of judo like respect, rule of law, discipline and diligent which are part of democracy and economic development.” He said the donation was also part of the sports diplomacy between Nigeria and Japan, while assuring the state of more support to other sports. For the chairman of LSJA Hammed, the gesture of the Japanese government would help to increase the popularity of the sport as well as encourage more people to take up the sport, even as he appealed to the Japanese government to help rehabilitate their judo hall at the Mobolaji Johnson Sports Complex in Rowe Park.